 Chapter 5 TCM network construction A core objective of network pharmacology is to reveal the multi-component, multi-target therapeutic mechanism of Traditional Chinese Medicine through network visualization. TCMDATA provides miscellaneous approaches based on ggtangle (network) and ggalluvial (Sankey diagram) for constructing and visualizing herb–molecule–target relationship networks: 5.1 Preparing the data All network visualizations start from the herb–molecule–target data frame returned by search_herb() or search_target(). library(TCMDATA) library(dplyr) # Query herbs and their molecular targets herbs &lt;- c(&quot;灵芝&quot;, &quot;黄芪&quot;) df &lt;- search_herb(herb = herbs, type = &quot;Herb_cn_name&quot;) df |&gt; head(10) #&gt; herb molecule target #&gt; 1 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid GAA #&gt; 2 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid POLB #&gt; 3 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid APP #&gt; 4 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA1 #&gt; 5 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA12 #&gt; 6 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA14 #&gt; 7 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA2 #&gt; 8 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA4 #&gt; 9 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA6 #&gt; 10 lingzhi 3,4-Dihydroxybenzoic acid CA7 The returned data frame contains three core columns: herb, molecule, and target, representing the tripartite relationship. 5.2 Sankey diagram visualization The Sankey diagram displays herb → molecule → target flows, with band width proportional to shared frequency. tcm_sankey() is powered by ggalluvial and supports rich color customization. 5.2.1 Basic usage library(ggplot2) # Subset to top molecules (by frequency) for readability top_mol &lt;- df %&gt;% count(molecule, sort = TRUE) %&gt;% head(8) %&gt;% pull(molecule) df_sub &lt;- df %&gt;% filter(molecule %in% top_mol) # Draw the Sankey diagram p_sankey &lt;- tcm_sankey(df_sub) print(p_sankey) Each vertical band represents a stratum (herb, molecule, or target), and the colored flows trace the associations between them. Wider bands indicate higher interaction frequency. 5.2.2 Customizing colors and appearance tcm_sankey() offers fine-grained control over color palettes, font style, flow transparency, and curvature: p_sankey2 &lt;- tcm_sankey( df_sub, herb_cols = c(&quot;#E41A1C&quot;, &quot;#377EB8&quot;), mol_cols = c(&quot;#66C2A5&quot;, &quot;#FC8D62&quot;, &quot;#8DA0CB&quot;, &quot;#E78AC3&quot;, &quot;#A6D854&quot;, &quot;#FFD92F&quot;, &quot;#E5C494&quot;, &quot;#B3B3B3&quot;), target_cols = c(&quot;#1B9E77&quot;, &quot;#D95F02&quot;, &quot;#7570B3&quot;, &quot;#E7298A&quot;, &quot;#66A61E&quot;, &quot;#E6AB02&quot;, &quot;#A6761D&quot;, &quot;#666666&quot;), font_size = 3.2, alpha = 0.35, knot.pos = 0.25 ) print(p_sankey2) Key parameters: Parameter Description herb_cols, mol_cols, target_cols Color vectors for each layer font_size Node label size alpha Flow transparency (0–1) knot.pos Curvature of flow bands (0–1) width Node/flow band width 5.3 Network graph with ggtangle While the Sankey diagram excels at showing flows, a force-directed network layout better reveals topological structure, hub nodes, and community patterns. prepare_herb_graph() builds an igraph object with pre-computed node metrics, and ggtangle renders it as a ggplot-based network. 5.3.1 Building the graph library(igraph) # Build the network (using a moderate subset for clarity) g &lt;- prepare_herb_graph(df, n = 60, compute_metrics = TRUE) # Inspect graph summary cat(&quot;Nodes:&quot;, vcount(g), &quot;
&quot;) #&gt; Nodes: 55 cat(&quot;Edges:&quot;, ecount(g), &quot;
&quot;) #&gt; Edges: 120 cat(&quot;Node types:&quot;, paste(unique(V(g)$type), collapse = &quot;, &quot;), &quot;
&quot;) #&gt; Node types: Herb, Molecule, Target prepare_herb_graph() automatically: Creates directed edges: Herb → Molecule → Target Computes per-node metrics: degree, centrality (eigenvector), betweenness, closeness, pagerank Assigns type labels ("Herb", "Molecule", "Target") to each node 5.3.2 Basic network visualization ggtangle extends ggplot2 to natively support igraph objects. You can use familiar aesthetics (color, size, shape) and layers (geom_point, geom_text_repel). library(ggtangle) library(ggrepel) set.seed(42) p_net &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;kk&quot;) + geom_edge(alpha = 0.3, color = &quot;grey60&quot;) + geom_point(aes(color = type, size = centrality)) + scale_color_manual(values = c( &quot;Herb&quot; = &quot;#E41A1C&quot;, &quot;Molecule&quot; = &quot;#377EB8&quot;, &quot;Target&quot; = &quot;#4DAF4A&quot; )) + scale_size_continuous(range = c(2, 8)) + theme_void() + labs(title = &quot;Herb–Molecule–Target Network&quot;, subtitle = &quot;Layout: Kamada-Kawai | Node size: Eigenvector centrality&quot;) print(p_net) In this plot: Red nodes represent herbs, blue represent molecules, and green represent targets. Larger nodes have higher eigenvector centrality, indicating greater topological importance. The Kamada-Kawai ("kk") layout positions strongly connected nodes closer together. 5.3.3 Adding node labels For networks with many nodes, ggrepel::geom_text_repel() prevents label overlap. Here we label only high-centrality nodes: set.seed(42) # Extract centrality threshold (top 30%) cent_thresh &lt;- quantile(V(g)$centrality, 0.7) p_labeled &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;kk&quot;) + geom_edge(alpha = 0.25, color = &quot;grey70&quot;) + geom_point(aes(color = type, size = centrality), alpha = 0.85) + geom_text_repel( aes(label = ifelse(centrality &gt;= cent_thresh, name, &quot;&quot;)), size = 3, max.overlaps = 25, segment.alpha = 0.4 ) + scale_color_manual(values = c( &quot;Herb&quot; = &quot;#E41A1C&quot;, &quot;Molecule&quot; = &quot;#377EB8&quot;, &quot;Target&quot; = &quot;#4DAF4A&quot; )) + scale_size_continuous(range = c(1.5, 9)) + theme_void() + labs(title = &quot;Labeled Network (Top 30% Centrality Nodes)&quot;) print(p_labeled) 5.3.4 Alternative layouts ggtangle supports all igraph layout algorithms. Common choices include: library(aplot) set.seed(42) base_layers &lt;- list( geom_edge(alpha = 0.25, color = &quot;grey70&quot;), geom_point(aes(color = type, size = centrality)), scale_color_manual(values = c( &quot;Herb&quot; = &quot;#E41A1C&quot;, &quot;Molecule&quot; = &quot;#377EB8&quot;, &quot;Target&quot; = &quot;#4DAF4A&quot;)), scale_size_continuous(range = c(1.5, 7)), theme_void() ) p_fr &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;fr&quot;) + base_layers + ggtitle(&quot;Fruchterman-Reingold&quot;) p_kk &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;kk&quot;) + base_layers + ggtitle(&quot;Kamada-Kawai&quot;) p_star &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;star&quot;) + base_layers + ggtitle(&quot;Star&quot;) p_nicely &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;nicely&quot;) + base_layers + ggtitle(&quot;Nicely (auto)&quot;) plot_list(p_fr, p_kk, p_star, p_nicely, ncol = 2) Layout Best for "kk" (Kamada-Kawai) Medium-sized networks with clear clusters "fr" (Fruchterman-Reingold) Dense networks; force-directed separation "star" Highlighting a central hub node "nicely" Automatic layout selection by igraph 5.3.5 Enriching the network with external data Using the %&lt;+% operator from ggfun, you can bind additional data to the network for richer visual encodings: # Create a data frame with node-level metrics node_df &lt;- data.frame( label = V(g)$name, type = V(g)$type, degree = V(g)$degree, betweenness = V(g)$betweenness, pagerank = V(g)$pagerank ) set.seed(42) p_enriched &lt;- ggplot(g, layout = &quot;kk&quot;) + geom_edge(alpha = 0.2, color = &quot;grey70&quot;) + geom_point(aes(color = type, size = degree), alpha = 0.85) + scale_color_manual(values = c( &quot;Herb&quot; = &quot;#E41A1C&quot;, &quot;Molecule&quot; = &quot;#377EB8&quot;, &quot;Target&quot; = &quot;#4DAF4A&quot; )) + scale_size_continuous(name = &quot;Degree&quot;, range = c(2, 10)) + theme_void() + labs(title = &quot;Network Colored by Node Type, Sized by Degree&quot;) print(p_enriched) 5.4 Comparing the two approaches Feature Sankey (tcm_sankey) Network (ggtangle) Best for Displaying flows and proportions Topology and hub detection Layout Fixed three-column Flexible (force-directed, circular, etc.) Node metrics Not applicable Degree, centrality, betweenness, PageRank Interactivity Static Extensible with ggiraph Scalability ~50–200 connections ~30–500 nodes Both visualizations are complementary: the Sankey diagram provides an intuitive overview of which herbs contribute which molecules to which targets, while the network graph reveals structural properties like hub molecules, bridge targets, and community modules. 5.5 Session information sessionInfo() #&gt; R version 4.5.0 (2025-04-11) #&gt; Platform: aarch64-apple-darwin20 #&gt; Running under: macOS 26.2 #&gt; #&gt; Matrix products: default #&gt; BLAS: /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/4.5-arm64/Resources/lib/libRblas.0.dylib #&gt; LAPACK: /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/4.5-arm64/Resources/lib/libRlapack.dylib; LAPACK version 3.12.1 #&gt; #&gt; locale: #&gt; [1] zh_CN.UTF-8/zh_CN.UTF-8/zh_CN.UTF-8/C/zh_CN.UTF-8/zh_CN.UTF-8 #&gt; #&gt; time zone: Asia/Shanghai #&gt; tzcode source: internal #&gt; #&gt; attached base packages: #&gt; [1] stats graphics grDevices utils datasets methods base #&gt; #&gt; other attached packages: #&gt; [1] aplot_0.2.8 ggrepel_0.9.6 ggtangle_0.0.7 igraph_2.2.1 #&gt; [5] ggplot2_4.0.1 dplyr_1.1.4 aplotExtra_0.0.4 ivolcano_0.0.5 #&gt; [9] enrichplot_1.28.4 TCMDATA_0.0.0.9000 #&gt; #&gt; loaded via a namespace (and not attached): #&gt; [1] DBI_1.2.3 gson_0.1.0 gridExtra_2.3 #&gt; [4] rematch2_2.1.2 rlang_1.1.6 magrittr_2.0.3 #&gt; [7] DOSE_4.2.0 compiler_4.5.0 RSQLite_2.4.2 #&gt; [10] ggalluvial_0.12.5 systemfonts_1.3.1 png_0.1-8 #&gt; [13] vctrs_0.6.5 reshape